  <span id="freeText125167064536942651" style="display:none">After a re-read of this recently, I'm bumping my rating to five stars. A really good read! I didn't love it as mch the first time I read jt for some reason. The story took a bit of time to unravel, and at first it was moving too slowly for me in my first read through, but I really warmed up to it. Johanna is a strong character, but she's very young when she's first married and violently abused by her husband. So it takes her time to come out of her shell and start asserting herself. But from the get go, Garwood really shows us that Johanna isn't weak in any way, shape or form and when Johanna finally does grow into her own, does she ever make everyone stand up and and notice of her. Literally. This character blew me away at the end and I have to say, really established herself as a vital, brave woman in her osn right, and perhaps just as fiercely protective of Gabriel as he is of her. I really love this character. <br /><br />And Garwood didn't disappoint with her hero. I can't resist the big, burly barbarians with soft hearts. Who can? Gabriel is infuriatingly protective, stubborn beyond a fault, mean even at times, but underneath it all he's a genlte soul. Just and loyal and true and what more do we want? I wasn't complaining. <br /><br />And this book was hysterical! I love how Garwood uses humor in her work. I'm literally laughing out loud when I read some of the scenes and that's a big plus. It goes a long way towards character development as well, and I'm all about well developed characters. All those puns about idioms were killing me. I wonder if even half of the idioms Johanna was using in her "lessons" had been invented at that time, even as mixed up as they were. I am however, fairly certain that the term romance, as Johanna uses it when she's thinking of Gabriel after she discovers his first name, was not a developed concept during the time period of this book. Personally, that doesn't bug me at all though I know it annoys some readers. However, I'm pretty darn certain with all the play on language, that Garwood thinks it amusing to play around with terms and phrases just to get a laugh out if her readers. And this reader is loving it. </span>
